---
import Layout from "@/layouts/layout.astro";
---

<Layout title="On Building Things - Venables">
  <header class="mb-12">
    <a
      href="/"
      class="text-xs font-mono text-muted-foreground uppercase tracking-[0.2em] mb-2"
    >
      Venables
    </a>
    <h1
      class="text-4xl md:text-5xl md:leading-none font-serif font-medium text-foreground mb-4 leading-tight text-pretty"
    >
      On Building Things That Matter
    </h1>
    <div class="text-sm font-mono text-muted-foreground">
      <time datetime="2024-12-15">December 15, 2024</time>
      <span class="mx-2">·</span>
      <span>5 min read</span>
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- Blog Content -->
  <article class="prose prose-neutral dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
    <div class="font-mono text-sm leading-relaxed space-y-6 text-foreground">
      <p>
        There's something deeply satisfying about building things from scratch.
        Not just the end result, but the entire process—the late nights
        debugging, the moments of clarity when a complex problem suddenly makes
        sense, the iterative refinement that transforms a rough idea into
        something elegant.
      </p>

      <p>
        I've been thinking about this a lot lately, especially as I work on
        projects that sit at the intersection of technology and human behavior.
        The tools we build don't exist in a vacuum; they shape how people think,
        work, and interact with the world around them.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-serif font-medium mt-8 mb-4 text-foreground">
        The Craft of Code
      </h2>

      <p>
        Writing code is often compared to writing prose, but I think it's more
        like architecture. Every decision—from the high-level system design down
        to variable naming—affects not just how the system works today, but how
        it can evolve tomorrow.
      </p>

      <p>
        Good code tells a story. It reveals the thought process behind the
        solution, makes assumptions explicit, and leaves breadcrumbs for future
        maintainers (often your future self). Bad code, on the other hand, is
        like a maze with no exit signs.
      </p>

      <blockquote
        class="border-l-2 border-muted-foreground pl-4 italic text-muted-foreground my-6"
      >
        "Programs must be written for people to read, and only incidentally for
        machines to execute." — Harold Abelson
      </blockquote>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-serif font-medium mt-8 mb-4 text-foreground">
        Building for Humans
      </h2>

      <p>
        The most successful tools I've built have one thing in common: they
        solve a real problem that I or someone I know actually has. Not a
        problem that sounds interesting in theory, but one that causes genuine
        friction in daily work.
      </p>

      <p>
        This is why I spend so much time talking to users, watching how they
        actually use the tools I build (not how I think they should use them),
        and iterating based on real feedback rather than assumptions.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-serif font-medium mt-8 mb-4 text-foreground">
        The Long Game
      </h2>

      <p>
        Building things that matter isn't just about the initial creation—it's
        about sustainability, maintainability, and evolution. The best projects
        I've worked on have grown organically over time, adapting to new
        requirements while maintaining their core simplicity.
      </p>

      <p>
        This requires discipline. It's tempting to add features, to make things
        more complex, to solve problems that don't exist yet. But the real skill
        is knowing what not to build, what to say no to, what to keep simple.
      </p>

      <p>
        In the end, the things that matter most are often the simplest: tools
        that work reliably, interfaces that feel intuitive, systems that get out
        of your way and let you focus on what's important.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- Navigation back -->
  <footer class="mt-16 pt-8 border-t border-border">
    <a
      href="/"
      class="inline-flex items-center text-sm font-mono text-muted-foreground hover:text-foreground transition-colors duration-200"
    >
      ← Back to home
    </a>
  </footer>
</Layout>
